{"title_page": "GM G platform (1995)", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2013}}\n{{main|GM G platform}}\n{{Infobox automobile platform\n| name             = GM G platform (FWD)\n| image            = Oldsmobile-Aurora.jpg\n| caption          = 2001-2003 Oldsmobile Aurora\n| aka              = G-Body\n| manufacturer     = [[General Motors]]\n| production       = 1995&ndash;2011\n| class            = [[Full-size]] \n| predecessor      = [[GM C platform (FWD)|GM C platform]]<br />[[GM E platform]]<br />[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]<br />[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n| successor        = [[GM Sigma platform]] (STS/SLS)<br />[[GM Epsilon platform]]<br />[[GM Omega platform]]<br />[[GM W platform]] (Aurora and LeSabre)<br />[[GM Zeta platform]] (Bonneville)\n| body_style       = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]<br>2-door [[coupe]]\n| engine           = \n| transmission     = \n| front_suspension = \n| rear_suspension  = \n| wheelbase        = \n| related          = [[GM C platform (FWD)]] <br /> [[GM H platform (FWD)]] <br /> [[GM K platform (FWD)]]\n| vehicles         = \n}}\n\nThe '''[[General Motors]] G platform''' (also called '''G-Body''') [[automobile platform]] designation was used for [[front-wheel drive]] [[full-size car|full-sized]] and [[luxury car]]s between 1995 and 2011.\n\nPreviously General Motors used the [[GM G platform (RWD)]] designation for unrelated [[mid-size car|mid-sized]] cars.\n\nThe G-body (the '''GMX690''') was based on [[Cadillac]]'s [[GM K platform (FWD)|K-body]] architecture. The platform was introduced in 1995 with [[Buick Riviera]] 2-door [[coupe]] (which moved up from the [[GM E platform]]) and the [[Oldsmobile Aurora]] 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] (a new model that replaced the Riviera-derived [[Oldsmobile Toronado|Toronado]]).  By the turn of the millennium, full-sized cars from four different GM makes were using some derivative of the platform.\n\n==Platform consolidation==\nStarting with the 1997 Buick Park Avenue, GM consolidated its four large-car platforms; [[GM C platform (FWD)|C platform]], [[GM K platform (FWD)|K platform]], [[GM H platform (FWD)|H platform]], and G platform; all to the G platform. However, GM decided to retain their previous platform designations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Frame|first=Phil|title=GM H CARS MOVE TO G PLATFORM|url=http://www.autonews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19950116/ANA/501160730#axzz2TYYYR1jT|work=[[Automotive News]]|accessdate=17 May 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.autonews.com%2Fapps%2Fpbcs.dll%2Farticle%3FAID%3D%2F19950116%2FANA%2F501160730%23axzz2TYYYR1jT&date=2013-05-17|archivedate=17 May 2013|date=16 January 1995}}</ref> These legacy platform designations were used in the VIN number and official GM publications. Models designated as \"G\" went out of production for MY 1999, but successor models were sold until MY 2011. \n\nThe G-body had an extremely resilient structure. For its time, the G-body was one of the strongest unibody car frames in production (25&nbsp;Hz). This fact did not go untouted as GM literature made much of the need to use a 'frame crusher' designed to test heavy-duty truck frames to finally break the G-body structure in their crush-to-failure procedures. Vehicles built on the G platform are also noted for having [[Seat belt#Belt-in-Seat .28BIS.29|belt-in-seat]] style seat belts like the mid-size [[GMT360]] SUVs. {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} The G-body also featured four-wheel [[independent suspension]] with a [[MacPherson strut]] style front suspension and a [[semi-trailing arm]] style rear suspension that utilized [[aluminum]] control arms. All-new aluminum control arms were introduced for the front suspension for 1998. {{citation needed|date=March 2014}} The handling was further enhanced with standard front and rear [[stabilizer bar]]s and lateral links in the rear suspension to further control wheel [[Toe (automotive)|toe]]. {{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\n===Vehicles===\n[[File:1999 Buick Riviera.jpg|250px|right|thumb|1999 Buick Riviera]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Years\n!Wheelbase\n!Model\n!Platform Name*\n|-\n|1995\u20131999||113.8&nbsp;in||[[Buick Riviera]]||GM G platform\n|-\n|1995\u20131999||113.8&nbsp;in||[[Oldsmobile Aurora]]||GM G platform\n|-\n|1997-2005||113.8&nbsp;in||[[Buick Park Avenue]]||[[GM C platform (1985)|GM C platform]]\n|-\n|1998\u20132004||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Cadillac Seville]]||[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n|-\n|2000\u20132005||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Buick LeSabre]]||[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]\n|-\n|2000\u20132005||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Pontiac Bonneville]]||[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]\n|-\n|2001\u20132003||112.2&nbsp;in||[[Oldsmobile Aurora]]||GM G platform\n|-\n|2000\u20132005||115.3&nbsp;in||[[Cadillac DeVille]]||[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> Official designation given by GM, despite using a G platform-derivative. This name also corresponds to the 4th letter in the [[VIN]] of the vehicle.\n\n==Revision==\nThe G platform was updated for the 2006 model year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buick Lucerne|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/news/buick-lucerne-auto-shows|work=[[Car and Driver]]|accessdate=17 May 2013|date=February 2005}}</ref>  The final car on this platform was the [[Buick Lucerne]], which ended production in June 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.just-auto.com/news/gm-axes-cadillac-dts-and-buick-lucerne_id111499.aspx|title=US: GM axes Cadillac DTS and Buick Lucerne|publisher=just-auto.com |date=2011-05-26 |accessdate=2011-06-05}}</ref>\n\n===Vehicles===\n[[File:Buick-Lucerne.jpg|right|thumb|2006 Buick Lucerne]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Years\n!Wheelbase\n!Model\n!Platform Name*\n|-\n|2006\u20132011||115.6&nbsp;in||[[Cadillac DTS]]||[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n|-\n|2006\u20132011||115.6&nbsp;in||[[Buick Lucerne]]||[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> Official designation given by GM, despite using a G platform-derivative. This name also corresponds to the 4th letter in the [[VIN]] of the vehicle.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[http://pp.kpnet.fi/haydee/GM_VIN_codes.htm List of GM VIN codes]\n{{General Motors platforms}}\n\n[[Category:General Motors platforms|G 2]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=December 2013}}\n{{main|GM G platform}}\n{{Infobox automobile platform\n| name             = GM G platform (FWD)\n| image            = Oldsmobile-Aurora.jpg\n| caption          = 2001-2003 Oldsmobile Aurora\n| aka              = G-Body\n| manufacturer     = [[General Motors]]\n| production       = 1995&ndash;2011\n| class            = [[Full-size]] \n| predecessor      = [[GM C platform (FWD)|GM C platform]]<br />[[GM E platform]]<br />[[GM H platform (1986)|GM H platform]]<br />[[GM K platform (1980)|GM K platform]]\n| successor        = [[GM Sigma platform]] (STS/SLS)<br />[[GM Epsilon platform]]<br />[[GM Omega platform]]\n| body_style       = 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]]<br>2-door [[coupe]]\n| engine           = \n| transmission     = \n| front_suspension = \n| rear_suspension  = \n| wheelbase        = \n| related          = [[GM C platform (FWD)]] <br /> [[GM H platform (FWD)]] <br /> [[GM K platform (FWD)]]\n| vehicles         = \n}}\n\nThe '''[[General Motors]] G platform''' (also called '''G-Body''') [[automobile platform]] designation was used for [[front-wheel drive]] [[full-size car|full-sized]] and [[luxury car]]s between 1995 and 2011.\n\nPreviously General Motors used the [[GM G platform (RWD)]] designation for unrelated [[mid-size car|mid-sized]] cars.\n\nThe G-body (the '''GMX690''') was based on [[Cadillac]]'s [[GM K platform (FWD)|K-body]] architecture. The platform was introduced in 1995 with [[Buick Riviera]] 2-door [[coupe]] (which moved up from the [[GM E platform]]) and the [[Oldsmobile Aurora]] 4-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]] (a new model that replaced the Riviera-derived [[Oldsmobile Toronado|Toronado]]).  By the turn of the millenniu